Wrapper¶

In [7]:
def wrapper(feature_list):
    return SFS(feature_list)

variable log format: [ (features selected + new candidate feature), performance after executing the current state]

In [8]:
def SFS(feature_list):
    features_selected = []
    log = [] # to record all the results for future information retrival
    bar = progressbar.ProgressBar(max_value=FEATURES) # defining the number of iterations for the progress bar
    # Do until no features left
    while len(feature_list) > 0:
        # run the pattern classifier for current state with prior selected features
        log.append(state_runner(feature_list, features_selected))
        # Find the maximum performance based on current features selected
        feature_list, features_selected = max_finder(feature_list, features_selected, log[-1])
        # update the progress bar
        bar.update(FEATURES - len(feature_list))
    return log
In [9]:
def state_runner(feature_list, features_selected):
    log = []
    # as the `feature_list` gets updated, we run the KNN with the previous features selected and new ones
    # also keep all the recored to compare and find the best possible
    for new in feature_list:
        r = pattern_classifier(X[:,(features_selected + [new])],y)
        # store the records in log
        log.append((features_selected + [new], r))
    return log

F1-score formula: \begin{equation} \textrm{f1-score}=\frac{TP}{TP+\frac{1}{2}(FP+FN)} \end{equation}

Pattern Classifier¶

Using K-Nearest Neighbours as our abjective function

In [10]:
def pattern_classifier(X, y):
    # splitting data into train and test
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20)
    # using K-NN classifier with 5 neighbours (default recommended K)
    classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
    # fitting the model
    classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # predicting the test set
    y_pred = classifier.predict(X_test)
    # getting required variables to calculate f1-score
    TN, FP, FN, TP = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred).ravel()
    # calculating f1-score
    f1 = TP /(TP + 0.5*(FP+FN))
    return f1
In [11]:
def max_finder(feature_list, features_selected, log):
    # comparing performances for each state to find the best state
    maxx = max(log,key=itemgetter(1))[0]
    # remove the feature from the list
    feature_list.remove(maxx[-1])
    # add feature to selected features list
    features_selected.append(maxx[-1])
    # return updated lists
    return feature_list, features_selected

Finding the best result

In [12]:
def get_optimal(log):
    maxx = (-1,-1)
    for state in log:
        if max(state,key=itemgetter(1))[1] > maxx[1]:
            maxx = (max(state,key=itemgetter(1))[0], max(state,key=itemgetter(1))[1])
    return maxx

Every variable's size¶

In [23]:
import sys
def sizeof_fmt(num, suffix='B'):
    ''' by Fred Cirera,  https://stackoverflow.com/a/1094933/1870254, modified'''
    for unit in ['','Ki','Mi','Gi','Ti','Pi','Ei','Zi']:
        if abs(num) < 1024.0:
            return "%3.1f %s%s" % (num, unit, suffix)
        num /= 1024.0
    return "%.1f %s%s" % (num, 'Yi', suffix)

for name, size in sorted(((name, sys.getsizeof(value)) for name, value in locals().items()),
                         key= lambda x: -x[1])[:10]:
    print("{:>30}: {:>8}".format(name, sizeof_fmt(size)))
